<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Yucca schidigera </i>is a highly variable, slow-growing plant that grows to 9 m in height. Individual plants may live for hundreds of years. Yucca moths pollinate the flowers, and moth larvae eat some of the seeds. Fruits are fleshy capsules that small mammals eat and disperse the seeds. Seedling establishment occurs under warm and moist conditions (Tirmenstein 1990b). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Yucca schidigera </i>is one of the characteristic shrubs at mid elevations in the eastern and central Mojave Desert and of the desert slopes of the Peninsular and Transverse ranges. In these areas, <i>Y. schidigera </i>rarely dominates but acts as an indicator species at low cover in stands at slightly lower elevations and on shallower soils than those of the <i>Yucca brevifolia </i>alliance. Some stands attain the highest shrub diversities, up to 30 species, found in hot deserts of California (J. André, pers. comm. 2000). Stands grade into those of the <i>Larrea tridentata- Ambrosia dumosa </i>alliance at lower elevations and at mid elevations into the <i>Coleogyne ramosissima, Ephedra nevadensis, Eriogonum fasciculatum, Grayia spinosa, </i>and <i>Salazaria mexicana </i>alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
