    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cb). Stands are occasional at upper elevations on the western margin of Anza- Borrego Desert State Park, where they mix with those of <i>Agave deserti</i> and <i>Larrea tridentata</i> alliances (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Af, Ah, Aj-p). Stands occur east of Victorville due to yucca’s preference for warm season rains (Desert Workshop 2000) where they regularly occur above 900 m. They replace <i>Yucca brevifolia</i> stands in certain sections of the Mojave National Preserve, but both may occur in the same area. Stands rarely have a <i>Pleuraphis rigida</i> understory; the most widespread associates are the <i>Larrea tridentata- Ambrosia dumosa</i> alliance (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba, Bc). Stands occur in Joshua Tree National Park and frequently have <i>Simmondsia chinensis</i> (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fe-f). Stands occur in the southern Coso and Panamint ranges.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi, Bp). Stands are common on slopes and upper bajadas at the base of mountains in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park, where they associate with those of <i>Agave deserti, Larrea tridentata,</i> and <i>Pleuraphis rigida</i> alliances (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) and in the Little San Bernardino Mountains in Joshua Tree National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance is naturally species-rich with much of its diversity due to non fire-adapted, slow-growing, non-sprouting shrubs. High fire frequencies will reduce shrub diversity and increase the cover of non-native annual grasses, <i>Senegalia greggii, Ericameria teretifolia, Eriogonum fasciculatum, Salazaria mexicana, </i>and other shrubs, especially if the fire-carrying annual grasses continue to increase in the desert. </div>
</div>

    

    

